<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I have to disagree a lot with this. It was my class more than a guild that decided that I was de<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->[/quote]<br>
<br>
Crydee's right, that in Vision, it's basicly up to your class leader who next from your class gets the assistance of the guild in doing your epic.  The class leaders work with the officers to keep the overall epic-rate fair, steady, and paced so that it doesn't contribute to the overall burnout rate in the guild.<br>
<br>
For example, Selan (our Shaman CL) picks the next shaman in line for an epic - and in the case of our Shaman it's a matter of having done the footwork, being in the right place at the right time, and then, in the case of ties, senority and participation.  Back when every shaman was tied (with no part of their epic done), our two most senior, participating, high-level Shaman, Cantra and Vaxumgax got their spears -- long before we were able to &quot;churn out&quot; Shaman epics.<br>
<br>
Obviously this plan works for some classes better than others.  100% of our Rogues, 100% of our Monks, 100% of our Rangers (at least Epic #1), 75% of our Druids, and 66% of our Wizards and Clerics (who play more than a day or two a week) have have epic weapons.  It's easy to be the &quot;next&quot; Druid when your class can churn them out.  It's not so easy to be the next Warrior (7%) sometimes.  It's especially not easy to be the 10th warrior on a list like that.<br>
<br>
The CLs and officers have an epic barometer of sorts.  Has the guild done too many recently?  Have we recruited monks and gone running around the world for them?  Normally the epic-light is green, but sometimes we put up the caution flag and keep epic raids to a minimum.<br>
